Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: Kakuzi, Kenya Airways Move

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-27T16:27:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kakuzi-kenya-airways-move.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell to its
lowest in more than 20 months, dropping 0.9 percent to 58.92 by
the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the capital. The Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index declined for a fifth day, sliding 0.8
percent to 20,015.63 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to a statement on the bourse’s  website . Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  rose for the first day in five, advancing 3.9
percent to 793.87 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek. In Mauritius,
the SEMDEX Index rose for the first time in four days, advancing
0.7 percent to 1,862.24 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index declined for a third
day, dropping 0.5 percent to 1,093.40 by the 3 p.m. close in
Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.        Kakuzi (KKZI)  Ltd, a Kenyan tea and fruit producer,
advanced for the first day in three, adding 1.5 shillings, or
2.3 percent, to 67.5 shillings. Tea production rose 5.6 percent
in August from the year earlier, according to data from the Tea
Board of Kenya.        Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
largest carrier, gained for the first time in seven days, rising
25 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 28 shillings. The airline plans to
begin flights to the Eritrean capital, Asmara, in 2012, amid
plans by Eritrea’s flag carrier to start flying to Kenya in
November, Business Daily reported.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
